This is something that I've wanted to do for a long time, and the latest
hassles with the currency system combined with a quote from someone about
Agoran Economics being nothing like a Currency Market and more like
a barter of Commodities, I finally sat down and wrote it.  (Probably
as a relaxation exercise to reduce the stress of my upcoming marriage-- 
48 hours, yipes! :))

So here is the rough first part of a PROTO, still being finished, that
completly wipes the Currency paradigm from the game.  The individual "Currencies"
remain, in a different guise, but I've done a lot to abolish the attempt
to shoehorn currency-centric concepts into the "economy."

Even so, I have tried hard to keep the Pragmatic form of the prior
Currency reform in place-- there are no automagical happenings without
a Player doing something, and if the player doesn't do something, it doesn't
get done, so there's no gamestate indeterminancy in my model.  (Brave words 
which I'll probably live to eat.)

Bear in mind that this is unfinished, there are a _lot_ of amendments that
still need to be added, but below is the heart of the Proposal.


Swann

PROTO:Objects
============================================================
PART I: Objects in General

The Rule Category "Currencies" is re-named "Objects"

Rule 1467 has its title change from "Definition of a Currency"
to "Definition of an Object"

Amend Rule 1467 (Definition of a Currency) to read as follows;

     There are entities known as Objects.  An entity is only an 
     Object if the Rules designate it as such.  All Objects, and all
     Classes of Objects conform to the following strictures:

       i) All individual Objects must be a member of one, and only one, 
          Class of Objects explicitly defined in the Rules.
      ii) All individual Objects are owned by one, and only one, entity. 
          Whenever the Rules do not specify an owner of an individual 
          Object, the owner of that individual Object is the Bank.
     iii) All Objects are indivisible. Entities may only own an integral 
          number of Objects.
      iv) An Object that is a member of Class X may be referred to as an
          X. (Where X is the name of the Class of Object.)
       v) Each Class of Objects has a Recordkeepor who must keep a
          current Record of all entities that own Objects belonging to 
          that Class, and the number of those Objects each entity 
          possesses.  If the Rules specify no Recordkeepor for an 
          Class of Objects, that Recordkeepor is the Chancellor.

     This Rule takes precedence over any other Rule defining the 
     properties of Objects or Classes of Objects.

{Comment: This begins a general pragmatic infrastructure to replace the
          current currency bureaucracy.  Currencies are to be replaced
          by Objects, with a much more general structure.}


Rule 1576 has its title change from "Names of Currencies" to
"Classes of Objects"

Rule 1576 (Names of Currencies) is amended to read as follows;

      Each Class of Object shall have a name, which must be distinct
      from the name of any other Class of Object.

      Any attempt to create a Class of Object with the same name as an
      already existing Class of Object fails.


Rule 1577 (Minimum Unit Quantities (MUQ)) is repealed.
{Comment: Objects are atomic entities.}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Convertibility of Objects}

     The Rules can specify that a certain number of Objects of one Class 
     are Convertible into a certain number of Objects of another Class. 
     Objects in the first Class may be referred to as Convertible 
     Objects.

     Convertibility means that if the Rules specify that N Objects of 
     Class X are Convertible into M Objects of Class Y (Where N and M 
     are two non-zero Integers and X and Y are two different Classes of 
     Objects.  In this case the Object from Class X is the Convertible 
     Object.), then any entity that owns N Objects of Class X may 
     Convert those Objects into M Objects of Class Y.
     
     Entities may only Convert Convertible Objects by methods specified 
     in the Rules.

     Convertibility is not commutative, if the Rules specify that that N 
     Objects of Class X are Convertible into M Objects of Class Y, that 
     does not imply the reverse, that that M Objects of Class Y are 
     Convertible into N Objects of Class X.

{Comment: This allows the Rules to establish general methods of
          conversion, which don't have to be reversible.  The closest we 
          ever had was when it was possible to buy Marks or Reform 
          Coins.  This will be utilized in this reform in two ways, one, 
          to create a "universal" currency that can be converted to 
          other useful Objects (as a new player reward, Speaker's 
          Gratuity, Champion's award.) and to allow Blots to be used as 
          "Debt Tokens" (see next Rule.)}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Restricted Convertibility}

     Restricted Convertibility means that the Rules specify that N
     Objects of Class X are Convertible into M Objects of Class Y, and
     either N or M is a negative integer.  Restricted conversions only
     take place when required by this Rule, and only proceed as
     described in this Rule.  This Rule takes precedence over all other
     Rules governing Convertibility.

     When N Objects of Class X are converted into -(M) Objects of Class
     Y (N and M being positive non-zero integers and X and Y being
     different Classes of Objects), N Objects of Class X owned by a
     specific entity are Destroyed, and simultaneously M Objects of
     Class Y are Destroyed in the possession of the same entity. This
     Conversion is only allowed if the entity doing the conversion
     possesses M or more Objects of Class Y.  In this Case, N Objects
     of Class X can be said to be Inversely Convertible into M Objects
     of Class Y.
     
     When -(N) Objects of Class X are converted into M Objects of Class
     Y (N and M being positive non-zero integers and X and Y being
     different Classes of Objects), N Objects of Class X owned by a
     specific entity are Created, and simultaneously M Objects of
     Class Y are Created in the possession of the same entity. This
     Conversion is only permitted to be done by the Recordkeepor of an
     Object, and only in the case when the Rules require eim to Transfer
     or Destroy an Object that an entity does not possess.  This is done
     only as described in other Rules. In this Case, N Objects of Class
     X can be said to be Negatively Convertible into M Objects of Class
     Y.

{Comment: It might not be directly obvious, but this handles the cases
          of Indulgences and Blots, Blots coming into being when the 
          attempt is made to (to use obsolete terminology) make a 
          Treasury go negative, while when an Indulgence is Converted, 
          it destroys itself and a Blot.}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Equivalence of Objects}

     The Rules can specify that a certain number of Objects of one Class 
     are Equivalent to a certain number of Objects of another Class. 
     Objects in one of these Classes are said to be Equivalent to
     Objects in the other Class.

     Equivalency means that if the Rules specify that N Objects of Class 
     X are Equivalent to M Objects of Class Y (Where N and M are two 
     non-zero Integers and X and Y are two different Classes of Objects.  
     In this case the Objects in Classes X and Y are Equivalent to each 
     other.), then any entity that owns N Objects of Class X may Convert 
     those Objects into M Objects of Class Y, and any entity that owns M 
     Objects of Class Y may Convert those Objects into N Objects of 
     Class X. (Equivalency implies Convertibility, but not vice versa.)

     Entities may only Convert Equivalent Objects by methods specified 
     in the Rules.
     
     In addition, Equivalent Objects may always be substituted for each 
     other as follows;  If the Rules specify that N Objects of Class X 
     are Equivalent to M Objects of Class Y, then wherever any Rule 
     specifies a value of "N Objects of Class X," that value may be 
     substituted by "M Objects of Class Y" (and vice versa) without 
     changing the meaning or interpretation of that Rule.  Equivalency 
     means the two values are synonymous.

     This Rule takes precedence over any Rule that specifies any value 
     in Objects that has Equivalency to other Objects.

{Comment:  This allows objects to be "equal" in some circumstances.  It
           is used later in the definition of Decimal Objects, allowing 
           smaller Objects that are "worth" 1/10 of another type of 
           Object.}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Multiples of Convertible or Equivalent Objects}

     If the Rules specify that N Objects of Class X are Convertible to M 
     Objects of Class Y (Where N and M are two non-zero Integers and X 
     and Y are two different Classes of Objects.), this also implies 
     that A*N Objects of Class X are Convertible to A*M Objects of Class 
     Y for all positive integral values of A.

     If the Rules specify that N Objects of Class X are Equivalent to M 
     Objects of Class Y (Where N and M are two non-zero Integers and X 
     and Y are two different Classes of Objects.), this also implies 
     that A*N Objects of Class X are Equivalent to A*M Objects of Class 
     Y for all integral values of A.

{Comment: While this seems intuitively obvious given the prior
          definitions, since we're dealing with integral values here, it 
          doesn't hurt to be explicit.}


Rule 1578 (Currency Recordkeepors) has its title change from "Currency Recordkeepors"
to "Object Records"


Rule 1578 (Currency Recordkeepors) is amended to read as follows;

     Every Recordkeepor of a given Class of Objects must, once a week, 
     publish a report that contains a list of all entities that own 
     Objects belonging to that Class, and the number of those Objects 
     each entity possesses. This record of ownership is known as the 
     "Actual State" of those Objects; entities only own Objects as 
     recorded by the Recordkeepor, and Objects exist only in those 
     numbers recorded by the Recordkeepor.

     There is also the "Legal State" of those Objects, which is the 
     record of ownership and number that reflects what the Recordkeepor
     would have recorded given adherence to the Rules, perfect
     knowledge, and absence of error.

     Within the Class of Objects e records, the Recordkeepor must record 
     every change in ownership or number of Objects that is mandated in 
     the Rules, and e must refrain from recording any change in 
     ownership or number of Objects that is not mandated in the Rules.  
     Willful disregard of this provision is an "Abuse of 
     Responsibility," a Crime defined in other Rules.

     If any Player believes that the Recordkeepor has produced a report 
     that states an Actual State for an Object (or set of Objects) which 
     is not also the Legal State for that Object (or set of Objects), e 
     may produce a Claim of Error alleging this.

     Whenever a CFJ (or an admitted COE) finds that at some point the 
     Actual State of an Object (or set of Objects) was not also the 
     Legal State of that Object (or set of Objects) the Recordkeepor for 
     that Object (or set of Objects) must adjust eir records so that the 
     Actual State of those Objects conforms to the Legal State of those 
     Objects as specified in the CFJ (or admitted COE).

     Object Records can be Ratified. The effect of such Ratification is 
     to change the Legal State of the recorded Objects to conform to the 
     Actual State of those Objects.

{Comment: This is the heart of the pragmatic nature of this proposal.
          Like "ratification" this Rule makes a distinct effort to 
          separate what the Game State is, and what our Reports record.  
          This however goes further by creating a "Legal State" distinct 
          from the "Actual State," this is meant to be an analogue, as 
          closely as possible, to our officers moving physical tokens 
          around-- if the officer makes a mistake and gives someone an 
          Object, the Object is actually given, there is no chance for a 
          game state being indeterminate.  The gamestate's what the 
          reports say, period.  The "Legal State" exists to allow the 
          correction of errors, it exists as a model of what the 
          gamestate should be.}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: When the Recordkeepor is not a Player}

     If the designated Recordkeepor of a Class of Objects ceases to be a
     Player, the Speaker shall fulfill that responsibility until a new
     Recordkeepor is selected according to whatever procedure
     applies.  If there is no procedure defined for selecting a new
     Recordkeepor, then all Objects within that Class are destroyed and
     that Class of Object ceases to exist.  It is the Speaker's duty
     to report this change to eimself as Recordkeepor.

{Comment: Part of the old version of the prior rule that no longer
          seemed to fit there.}


Rule 1579 (Mintors) is repealed.
Rule 1722 (Minting of Currencies) is repealed.
Rule 1471 (Creation and Destruction of Currencies) is repealed.

{Comment: Mintors and Mint Authority are actually a hindrance to this
          reform, in that they add additional conditions to the legal 
          status of moves, and actually increase the bureaucratic 
          minutiae required to perform some basic actions, like 
          Converting an Object.  It also prevents the Object scheme from 
          addressing our "non-currency" Objects like Blots and Kudos.}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Legal Changes to Objects}

     To have effect, whenever the Rules specify a Transfer, a Creation, 
     or Destruction, of an Object, they must also specify a Player who 
     is to send a message to that Object's Recordkeepor to notify em of 
     the change.  The change only happens if the following conditions 
     hold.

       i) The Rules mandate the change.
      ii) The Rules specify a Player to report the change to the 
          Recordkeepor.
     iii) The specified Player reports the change to the Recordkeepor.

     If all these conditions hold, then the change reported by the 
     Player becomes the Legal State of that Object.

{Comment: Note that this specifies the requirements to change the "Legal
          State" of an object. (see: Object Records)  Note that if the 
          above rule invalidates a move, and we discover it much later, 
          there's still no gamestate indeterminance, at worst the 
          Recordkeepor will have to revise eir records to conform the 
          Object Records to the Legal State of the game, but this would
          not invalidate any moves subsequent to the error.}


Rule 1721 (The Chancellor) is amended to read as follows;

      There shall exist the Office of Chancellor.

      The Chancellor shall retain a schedule, listing every Class of
      Object, its Name and its Recordkeepor. This schedule shall be
      posted to the Public Forum by the Chancellor at least once in
      each Month.

{Comment: MUQ's and Mintors no longer exist.}


Rule 1599 (Failure to Execute Payment Orders) is repealed
Rule 1598 (Transfer Orders) is repealed
Rule 1730 (Delayed Transfer Orders) is repealed
Rule 1731 (Implicit Transfer Orders) is repealed
Rule 1596 (Payment Orders) is repealed
Rule 1732 (Satisfaction of Payment Orders) is repealed
Rule 1733 (Disputed Payment Orders) is repealed
Rule 1734 (Vacated Payment Orders) is repealed

{Comment: This repeals the Transfer Order/Payment Order bureaucracy,
          cutting down immensely on the paperwork required for simple
