Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Transferring Objects}

     When an Object is Transferred it ceases to be owned by one entity, 
     and simultaneously becomes owned by another entity.

     An Object is Legally Transferred when the Player designated by the 
     Rules to report the Transfer, reports the Transfer, the original
     owner of the Object, and the new owner of the Object, to that
     Object's Recordkeepor.  At this point the transfer is part of the
     Legal State of that Object.

     An Object is Actually Transferred when the Recordkeepor for that 
     Object records the change in ownership for that Object.  At this 
     point the change becomes part of the Actual State of that Object.

     The Recordkeepor must match every Legal Transfer with a 
     corresponding Actual Transfer.

     If a Recordkeepor commits the willful initiation of Actual 
     Transfers that correspond to no Legal Transfers, e is guilty of the 
     Crime of "Abuse of Responsibility" as defined in other Rules.

{Comment: The language here mirrors the language in Object Reports.
          Yes, theoretically the Recordkeepor could make all sorts
          of real transfers, but that is a criminalized act.  This,
          IMHO, is how "pragmatic" recordkeeping should be handled,
          W/O a mountain of paperwork.}


Create a Rule with the following text;
{Title: Creation or Destruction of Objects}

     When an Object is Created it comes into existence owned by a 
     specific entity.  When an Object is Destroyed, some specific entity 
     with at least one of those Objects has one of those Objects cease 
     to exist.

     An Object is Legally Created when the Player designated by the 
     Rules to report the Creation, reports the Creation, and the owner 
     of the Created Object, to that Object's Recordkeepor.  At this 
     point the Creation is part of the Legal State of that Object.

     An Object is Legally Destroyed when the Player designated by the 
     Rules to report the Destruction, reports the Destruction, and the 
     owner of the Destroyed Object, to that Object's Recordkeepor.  At 
     this point the Destruction is part of the Legal State of that 
     Object.

     An Object is Actually Created or Destroyed when the Recordkeepor 
     for that Object records the change for that Object.  At this point 
     the change becomes part of the Actual State of that Object.

     The Recordkeepor must match every Legal Creation with a 
     corresponding Actual Creation.

     The Recordkeepor must match every Legal Destruction with a 
     corresponding Actual Destruction.

     If a Recordkeepor commits the willful initiation of Actual 
     changes (Creations or Destructions) that correspond to no Legal
     changes, e is guilty of the Crime of "Abuse of Responsibility" as
     defined in other Rules.

{Comment: See comment above}


Let the following Rule be created;
{Title: Conversion of Objects}

     When N Objects of Class X are converted into M Objects of Class Y 
     (N and M being integers and X and Y being different Classes of 
     Objects), N Objects of Class X owned by a specific entity are 
     Destroyed while simultaneously M Objects of Class Y are Created in 
     the possession of the same entity.

     The owner of a Convertible Object(s) can cause that Object to be 
     converted by reporting to the Recordkeepor of that Object: 

       i) That e is Converting his Object(s)
      ii) The Number and Class of Objects being Converted
     iii) and the Number and Class of the Objects e is Converting them
          to.

     If the specified Object and Number is Convertible into the 
     specified Object and Number, then the Conversion becomes part of 
     the Legal State of those Objects.

     When the Recordkeepor of an Object of Class X  receives the report 
     of a Legal Conversion of N Objects of Class X into M Objects of 
     Class Y (all in the possession of one entity) e must, as soon as
     possible, record the Actual Destruction of N Objects of Class X
     (possessed by that entity) and report the Legal Creation of M
     Objects of Class Y (in the possession of that entity) to the
     Recordkeepor of Objects of Class Y.

     The report of the Conversion of Object X is also the report of the 
     Destruction of Object X.

{Comment: This should be fairly straightforward given the prior rules.}


Rule 1713 (Debt) is amended to read as follows;

     Whenever the Rules require that Objects be Transferred from an 
     entity, or that Objects possessed by an entity are to be 
     Destroyed, and upon the report of this Legal Transfer or Legal 
     Destruction, the entity possesses fewer Objects of the type
     specified then are required to be Transferred or Destroyed, 
     the Recordkeepor of that Object shall do the following before e
     makes the required Actual Transfers or Destructions:

      i) If the Objects being Transferred or Destroyed are Negatively 
         Convertible into Blots, e shall Convert -(M) of those Objects 
         into Blots possessed by the entity.  (Where M is the difference 
         between the number of those Objects the entity possesses and 
         the number of those Objects being Transferred or Destroyed.)

     ii) If the Objects being Transferred or Destroyed are not 
         Negatively Convertible into Blots, but are Equivalent to 
         Objects of Class Y that are, then e shall Convert -(N) Objects 
         of Class Y into Blots possessed by the entity. (where N is the 
         smallest value which will produce a number of Objects of Class 
         Y Equivalent to a number of the original Objects equal to or 
         greater than the difference between the number of those Objects 
         the entity possesses and the number of those Objects being 
         Transferred or Destroyed) Then e shall Convert all Objects of 
         Class Y that were Created into Objects of the original class.

    iii) If neither i) or ii) hold, e shall Create, in the possession of 
         the entity, (N) Blots and (N) of the Objects being Transferred 
         or Destroyed. (Where M is the difference between the number of 
         those Objects the entity possesses and the number of those 
         Objects being Transferred or Destroyed.)

     The Recordkeepor for the Object in question is charged with 
     reporting these changes to the appropriate Recordkeepors.

{Comment: There is no such thing as Persistent Indebtedness anymore.  If
          you go into debt, you get a Blot for each Object you're short.
          Blots become a sort of "negative Object."}


Let the following rule be created;
{Title: Transferable Objects}

     The Rules can define certain Classes of Objects as Transferable.  A 
     Transferable Object shall be Transferred whenever an owner of such 
     an Object wishes that Object to be Transferred to another entity 
     that is permitted to own that Object.  The owner of that Object 
     shall report this Transfer to the Recordkeepor of that Object.

{Comment: A basic Rule to cover transfers between Players.}


Let the following rule be created;
{Title: Decimal Objects}

     The Rules can define certain Classes of Objects as Decimal.  For 
     every Class of Decimal Objects X defined in the Rules there is also 
     another Class of Objects called deci-X, where X is the name of the 
     Class of Decimal Objects.

     One Object of Class X is Equivalent to ten Objects of Class deci-X.  
     It is permissible to record combined values of X Objects and deci-X 
     Objects in decimal notation. (i.e. saying "2.5 Objects of Class X" 
     is synonymous with saying "2 Objects of Class X and 5 Objects of 
     Class deci-X."

     The Recordkeepor for deci-X Objects is the same as the Recordkeepor 
     for X Objects.  If X Objects are Transferable, deci-X Objects are
     also Transferable.  If X Objects are Negatively Convertible into
     Blots, deci-X Objects are not.

{Comment: Allows a scheme for "fractional" objects w/o having them
          actually divisible.}


Let the following rule be created;
{Title: Personal Objects}

     The Rules can define certain Classes of Objects as Personal.  
     Personal Objects are only permitted to remain in the possession of 
     Players or the Bank.  If a Personal Object is in the possession of 
     a non-Player entity, then the Recordkeepor of that Object must 
     immediately transfer that Object to the non-Player Entity's 
     Executor if such exists.  If no such Executor exists, then e must 
     Transfer the Object to the Bank.

     The Recorkeepor is charged with detecting and reporting these
     changes.

{Comment: There are a number of Objects that we want to restrict to 
          Players. Blots and Kudos being two that come to mind right 
          now.  If we ever re-introduce something like Win Tokens, they 
          should be Personal as well. Note, this is not an automagical
          process, a Blot could exist in a Group treasury, but it would
          be illegal for the Herald to let it stay there.}


Let the following Rule be created;
{Title: Objects Changed by Proposal}

     If a Proposal directly orders changes to any Objects, and does not 
     itself specify a Player to report those changes to the 
     Recordkeepors of those Objects, then the Assessor shall report 
     those changes.

{Comment: Prevents a potential conflict with some prior Rules.}


Let the following Rule be created;
{Title: Reporting Object Changes, Timing}

     Whenever the Rules require a Player to report a change in an Object 
     to that Object's Recordkeepor, that Player shall make eir Report of 
     the change as soon as possible after the Rules require em to do so.

     Whenever a Recordkeepor of an Object receives a report in the 
     change of an Object, and that report caused a change in the Legal 
     State of that Object, e must then make the corresponding change in 
     the Actual State of that Object as soon as possible after receiving 
     the report.

{Comment: Fine point here, a change can be a Legal Change if never
          received by the Recordkeepor, but if so, e's not bound by the
          ASAP clause to make the Actual Change until a COE or CFJ finds
          the omission.}

